 tendency to become "party-states," or single-party regimes in which the head of state uses the party as a means of control. The speed and extent of these changes depend on the countervailing power of independent interest groups, such as business associations, farmers, or professionals. Widner's study offers important insights into the dynamics of party systems in Africa.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / Africa / General.2bisacsh  a20th century african history.  a20th century kenyan history.  aautocrat.  acorruption.  adaniel arap moi.  adictator.  agovernmental control.  ahead of state.  ahuman rights abuses.  ahuman rights.  ajomo kenyatta.  akadu.  akanu.  akenya african national union.  akenya.  akenyan african democratic union.  akenyan history.  akenyan politics.  aparty states.  apolitical climate.  apresident of kenya.  aregimes.  arepressive government.  asingle party system.  asurveillance.  awatchdog.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052007624240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520911857?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520911857423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520911857/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY